@node P1 "Overview of AHelp"
@toc "main"


Hello folks!  While using a popular (yet flawed) operating system's HELP command,
a thought popped into my head.  "Hrm...  Why doesn't AmigaDOS have a help
command?"  After getting over the shock that my brain had actually worked on
forming an idea, I decided to get cracking on AHelp.  This was the easy part.

"Great, " I thought to myself.  "Now I need to type in the entire AmigaDOS section
in the 'Using the System Software' book."  This was the hard part.

AHelp is a program much like MS-DOS's "FASTHELP" or UNIX's "MAN" command.  It's
basically a text searching/displaying program.  The chunk of the package is the
@{"HELP.LIBRARY" link P5}, which is a huge text file full of AmigaDOS commands and descriptions.

@endnode


@node P2 "Using AHelp"
@toc "main"

Here's how you use AHelp.


		HELP <command>  

			This displays help on the specified command.

		HELP <character>
		 
			This will list all commands beginning with the given 
			character.

		HELP
		
			This lists all commands who have help available.

		HELP ?

			This gives the the same information you're reading now.


	Any questions? =^)

@endnode

@node P3 "Adding commands"
@toc "main"

To add commands to the 'Help.library', simply load it into your favorite text editor 
(I used MEmacs) and follow this entry format:

		<command name>
		
				<help text body>
 
		#
		<command name>
		
				<help text body>
		
		#

		etc...

	Note the pound (#) sign at the end of the command blocks.  This
	informs AHelp that it has reached the end of the help text for that
	command.  Without it, AHelp would display the text for every command!


			A little about the !...

You may come across the "!" character somewhere within the Help.library.  This
tells AHelp to wait for the Enter key to pressed by the user.  "!" will display
the text following it.  

	Example:
	
		!Press ENTER to see example:
@endnode
	
@node P4 "Who is responsible for this?"
